727. Babylonica Chaldaeum (contracted gen. plur.). Munro quotes from Vitruvius on the scientific doctrines of the Chaldees. Berosus, a priest of Belus in Babylon, left the chaldaeam, and spread his doctrine about in Asia that the moon was spherical, half white, half blue. Duff adds that the Chaldaeans, his successors, were disliked by the scientific astronomers (astrologi, 1. 728) as being soothsayers and astrologers. They are mentioned with con- tempt by Juvenal in vi. 55 3—6 and x. 94 cum grege Chaldaeo. The terms Chaldaei, mathematici were generally reserved for fortune- tellers who made use of the stars. They were frequently expelled by the Senate from Italy, but as frequently returned. Tac.
